What It Will Take to Deter Russia 
The Lessons of the U.S. Failure in Ukraine in 2014 
By Jim Townsend 
January 7, 2022 
Armed forces after seizing control of the Simferopol airport in Crimea, Ukraine, February 2014  
Armed forces after seizing control of the Simferopol airport in Crimea, Ukraine, February 2014  
Baz Ratner / Reuters 
Sign in and save to read later 
Print this article 
Share on Twitter 
Share on Facebook 
Send by email 
Get a link 
 
Nearly eight years after Russia invaded Ukraine and illegally annexed Crimea, triggering a raft of international sanctions, the United States and its allies find themselves again trying to figure out how to deter Moscow from menacing Ukraine—if not launching a full-scale invasion—in hopes of gaining new Western concessions. Talks between U.S. President Joe Biden and Russian President Vladimir Putin have begun in earnest, with Putin putting forth maximalist demands that could become either the starting point for protracted negotiations that meet somewhere in the middle or, if left unmet, the pretext for a major escalation in the 
